Similarity measure¶

  • https://docs.opencv.org/3.4.15/df/dfb/group__imgproc__object.html#ga3a7850640f1fe1f58fe91a2d7583695d
  • https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55469431/what-does-the-tm-ccorr-and-tm-ccoeff-in-opencv-mean
In [97]:
def sim_ccorr(m1, m2):  # https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.multiply.html
    return np.sum(m1*m2)

Procedure¶

Raw implementation¶

In [98]:
im = cv2.cvtColor(im_input, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY).astype(np.uint32)
im_template = cv2.cvtColor(im_pattern_rotated, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY).astype(np.uint32)
In [99]:
h, w = im.shape
template_h, template_w = im_template.shape
In [100]:
%%time
sim_map = np.zeros((h - template_h, w-template_w))
for y in range(h - template_h):
    for x in range (w-template_w):
        sim_map[y, x] = sim_ccorr(im[y:y+template_h, x:x+template_w], im_template)

Wall time: 17.3 s

In [107]:
res = cv2.matchTemplate(im,im_template,cv2.TM_CCORR)

im_show = im_input.copy()
threshold = 0.85* np.max(res)
loc = np.where( res >= threshold)
for pt in zip(*loc[::-1]):
    cv2.rectangle(im_show, pt, (pt[0] + template_w, pt[1] + template_h), (0,0,255), 2)

Tasks¶

  • Compare execution time between the two implementations.

    • The raw implementation has a significantly longer execution time compared to the OpenCV implementation. Specifically, the raw implementation takes about 17.4 seconds, whereas the OpenCV implementation takes just 75.4 milliseconds. This indicates that OpenCV's cv2.matchTemplate function is highly optimized compared to the manual (raw) implementation that uses nested for-loops. While the raw implementation provides more granular control over the pattern matching process, its cost in terms of efficiency is evident.

  • Why there are some pacmans better detected than others?

    • The blue enemie has a high contrast with the red colour enemie that we use as pattern. And the treshold to detect it may be lower than the one that we use (0.85). Moreover, the other enmies that are not detected in the firs try, us because the enemie is going to diffrents directions and are not the same as the one we use as pattern (red enemie). The only one enemie detected in the first try seems to be the most similar to our pattern, because the enemie is going to the same direction and there are not obstacles as the other enemies with the enemie body, as walls or the little points.

  • Change the size of the pattern image (cv2.resize). How do the results change?

    • As smaller the resize is, more false positives are happening, because as more smaller is the pattern, less pixels will be needed to match with it. And as biggest is the resize, less false positives because as bigger as the pattern will be, more pixels will be in the comparison and more pixels will be include in the function.

  • Make a slight rotation of the pattern image (cv2.rotate). How do the results change?

    • With the rotation, the PACMAN is identified. That can be happening because when the pattern is rotated, I changed its spatial orientation. This can make it match areas in the original image it previously didn't. Specifically for Pac-Man, its slightly asymmetrical shape due to the open "mouth" might now align better with the image after rotation, improving the match. Moreover, it can see a better accuracy detecting the enemies.

  • What could be the utility of the rotation and the resize of the template image?

    • In general, the rotation and resizing of the template image serve as essential tools to enhance detection accuracy. Dute to in real world, the objects have different spatial orientations, without the flexibility to adjust the template, the matching process can easily miss or misidentify these objects.
